listing.name: St John at Hackney Brewery x Ela
listing.subtitle: Beautiful Beer & Cypriot Kebabs

tip.text:
A brewery and food joint in a renovated railway arch might not have you rubbing your eyes in shock, but there's plenty more to this place than meets those eyes. Ostensibly, it's a brewery and taproom with a rotating kitchen out back, but the attention to detail here is quite a sight - from the way they make their beer in vats that would have Walter White raising his eyebrows, to the understated beauty of their huge window facade and the 200-year-old church pews that line the walls.

The result is a damn fine place to have a high quality beer (they have 11 lagers, ales and stouts on tap) and get full. It's also deeply rooted in the community, with heavy involvement in local projects in collab with the church of the same name.

Out back is a kitchen currently inhabited by Ela, creators of simple, incredibly tasty Cypriot food. Inspired by the 'world's best kebab shop' in Cyprus, their 'babs come in wondrously marinated chicken, pork or halloumi variations stuffed full of slaws, feta, currents and salads. Big enough to share, these are truly tasty bites. Add in a nice sun-trap garden and hefty speakers and you've got a suitable spot to kick back and let some nice times roll.

listing.name: The Taproom at London Fields Brewery
listing.subtitle: Craft Beer & Bites

tip.text: This is the taproom of the London Fields Brewery empire, and a deceptively good place to enjoy one of LFB's damn fine craft beers on tap or some beer-friendly grub. That food has a decidedly German influence: indulgent dishes like schnitzel, beer-cheese dumplings and a halloumi beetroot burger all feature on the weekend menu. It's a fairly simple affair inside with a stripped back aesthetic, but this place is not just about beer - you'll also find organic wine, cocktails and live jazz on Sundays.

Drink straight from a 40FT shipping container tank every weekend at Dalston's friendly neighbourhood brewery. This is the kinda place where you can test craft beers to your heart's content - or your wallet's discontent. With empty kegs as seats and tables, beer straight from the tank, brewery tours and live music, these guys mean business.

This unassuming taproom may not be the easiest to find, but that only adds to its charm - and explains the vibey atmosphere they got going on. A small spot with big personality, the crowd is a mixture of die-hard beer fans, average Joes with above-average stories, and the odd lost hipster - the gentle buzz of conversation bounces off the cladded arches for added ambience.

Their sour beer deserves a mention in particular - the selection is wide-ranging, tangy, and so damn delicious, but all of their beer is brewed on site, so you can bet your bottom dollar that they all go down a treat.

Mother Kelly is a bit like that friend's mum you had when you were young who let you run wild: a great host, a bit of a mess, but would always let you drink in the house and eat your takeaway in the living room.

Seemingly inspired by the NYC subway system, it's all graffiti and corrugated iron here. And the bevs? You're looking at 23 regularly changing taps and a mind boggling range of bottles. If you're the indecisive type, however, they have you covered - just ask the staff to guide you or pick you something blind. Street food trucks pull up outside from Thursday to Sunday which is pretty sweet too. Kelly's cool with whatever, man.

Fancy a pint of the good stuff? Keg or barrel? How about a whole blooming tank? Howling Hops, London's first dedicated tank bar, serves ten of their own pale ales and craft beers from the ten massive tanks behind their bar. Because they never sees the open air and are drunk within weeks of being made, the ales are about as fresh and tasty as they're ever gonna get. For something different, try the Riding Ale - it's light at 3% but the distinct zesty flavours could knock your knickers off.

Food-wise you can't miss the 'big fuck off tray of meat' (please excuse their French) - a simple platter piled high with cuts of beef, lamb, pork, sausages, roast veg and salad on the side. The decor is nothing fancy, but remember you're here for the beer.

This is what canal-side dreams are made of. This craft beer brewery was Hackney Wick's first, and remains the best. Housed in a former print factory, the industrial space is a siren song to East Londoners - especially in summer, when you can dine al fresco on some pretty scrumptious pizzas.

This is a local spot through and through - the interior is made with reclaimed materials sourced from local artists. You can even chill in the boats that are moored up during summer. Nice.

There's a little clue in the name of this one to what goes on behind closed doors - turns out they've a micro-brewery locked away in the basement. One Mile Brewery (now a big baller brewery up in Tottenham) was born in this very basement, which they now keep for the more experimental batches.

No surprise then to find plenty of One Mile brews on sale, along with a few other London-focused craft beers, plenty of spirits and wine. Pub grub is head-and-shoulders above average - we had a haddock and chips that was bang on the money. Pair that with the low-key decor - mis-matched furniture, comfy sofas, old road signs - an you've got a pretty welcoming pub.

Look out for live jazz on Sundays and quiz night Thursdays.

Born over a pint, this Leyton-based start-up is centred on a joint love of music and beer. There's nothing worse than a shit pint at a gig - and the two lads behind signature brew are hell-bent on changing things. To do so, music artists are invited to brew their own beer at their brewery which is then sold to their fans. What's in it for you? You can come and taste these delicious brews in their taproom - from Backstage IPA, to Red Wedge and Signature Pale.

Opening times can vary so give 'em a call before rocking up.

Every time we take a look at Tottenham, its star seems to be burning a 'lil brighter and nothing shows that more than Five Miles. This cavernous warehouse space is fitted with a bar, cafe, brewery, restaurant and club spot with nifty minimalist interiors complimented by friendly communal vibes and a very dope sound system. It's quickly become a destination worth traipsing up north for.

By tap, you're looking at twenty different brews including five from the on-site brewery, Affinity Brew Co. There are also negronis and espresso martinis, which sounds a surefire recipe for personal disaster. Meanwhile in the kitchen, Torshi are doing brunch and dinner with sharing menus featuring bits like fried chicken with pickled watermelon rind and zhoug and Yemeni falafel. Very tasty stuff.

What really makes this spot stand out, though, is the sound system and eclectic range of nights they put on within the 250 capacity spot. With a 4am licence and proximity to the Victoria line, this is just the type of late-night hub putting Tottenham on the map.

Cult Danish brewer Mikkel Borg Bjergs has a name that rings out in craft beer circles (trust us on that one). Having done it in Denmark for years, he's teamed up with, erm... *checks notes* Rick Astley to bring Shoreditch a Mikkeler bar. Sure, whatever. A stylish, one-room taproom where 15 in-house and 5 guest brews are available by the third, the two-thirds or the pint. These are artfully crafted beers that excite the palette, stimulate the palette, and ask questions of the palette that sometimes the mind cant answer. Such as: What is that flavouring? And, yes, that artisan goodness comes at a fairly high price.

Inside there's a distinctively minimalist Scandinavian touch, with pastel greens, clean lines and large orbs of light. Its quietly cool and sophisticated, making it clear that this really isnt the one for a session with the boys; instead it's for a solo connoisseur, a post-work tipple, or an evening-starter before heading on elsewhere. When it gets busy - and it does - those hard surfaces dont do much for the acoustics, so youll have to lean in close to make yourself heard.

Many a brewery has seen the vacant lands of Tottenham's industrial patch as prime brewing estate and jumped on it, including Pressure Drop. From their humble beginnings in a garden shed back in 2012, they're growing at a nice enough rate and now open a tap room on Saturdays where their assortment of beers and ales are available for purchasing, card only, at 2.50 a glass.

address.line1: 2 Lockwood Industrial Estate, Mill Mead Road

tip.text:
This lot have been supplying the thirsty people of London with quality craft beers since 2013. They started off with a couple of tubs in De Beauvoir Town and took on the cockney name for the area (Beavertown), then moved to Hackney, and finally, when their operation got too big they coped a whole chunk of industrial estate in Tottenham.

Settle yourself among the heavy machinery or out in the sunshine, and order one of their finest brews which range from black IPAs to 9% smoked porters. We're pretty partial to an easy-drinking, crisp-tasting Neck Oil; or if you're feeling really fancy, try one of their 'wild' beers from the Tempus Project. Made in small batches, aged in breathable wooden barrels for three or more months with wild yeasts and rogue bacterial strains, these babies are ripe pickings for the more sophisticated drinker.

Their taproom is only open between 2 and 8pm every Saturday, so your window of opportunity to actually drink the beer is pretty limited. Get in and on it.

Extending their reach across East London, Long Arm Pub and Brewery has opened up an on-site urban farm, micro-brewery and distillery to accompany its main Ealing site. This Worship Street pub is a bit of a game changer - featuring a super-sustainable system that totally eliminates the need for packaging so your pint can travel the merest of metres from grain to glass.

With its graffitied walls and exposed brickwork you'd expect the Long Arm to be more hipster than substance, but once you guzzle down one of their sassy homegrown beer-based cocktails and dip into their delicious fish tacos, you'll be satisfied that this isn't your run of the mill Shoreditch pub. Ok maybe it is, but it definitely tastes a whole lot better than most.

Born in the basement of the White Hart Brew Pub in Whitechapel all the way back in 2014, One Mile Brewery brews up some seriously tasty liquids. It's since moved all the way up north to Tottenham but apparently still brew some funky flavours down in the bottom of that pub.

They cook up all sorts - including bitters, IPAs, lagers, pale ales, porters, stouts, wheat beer and even a gluten-free number (perfect for that one pal you have that's allergic). Saturdays in the summer they open up their doors to the common folk (like you and we) and serve up this liquid gold on tap - a taproom if you will.

Wildcard have been at their alchemy in this spot for a couple of years now but theyve come from the humblest of beginnings. Two guys met working in Boots before going off to university where they tried their hand at brewing, from bedrooms to bathtubs. Now though they're properly legit and whipping up some magical flavours, open to us muggles Friday through Sunday. We strongly recommend you dip your beak in their Black IPA.

Thurston Moore of Sonic Youth has played here before and is looking to do more shows in the near future. Wildcards William tells us that the plan moving ahead is to throw more gigs, maybe build a small platform and get more of their crafty kegs around town.

This cosy beer den has its roots in Portsmouth so we're very happy to see it set up shop in London town. Whilst it does food, we wouldn't really tip you coming for that; instead it's all about the brews with an in-house working brewhouse which offers 'create your own' brewing sessions and enlightening brewery tours.

Unlike a lot of crafty newcomers, Southwark Brewing company has been around for 30 years - ok so that's not that long, but still. Being nestled in one of the arches on Druid Street, it's a regular stop on the Bermondsey beer mile, and maybe even the best according to some sources!

No frills here, just a few benches, picnic tables and some standing room. You're here for the beer and the good times. Ask the lovely lot behind the bar for some advice or tuck into the hoppy pleasures of their Bermondsey Best. If you're lucky, they may even have a seasonal something on to tickle the sour, citrusy ends of your palate.

Take that Heineken and throw it straight into the Thames - don't worry about polluting the ocean, your beer-drinking credentials are far more important than marine vitality. To continue the metaphor, jump in after your floating can and swim down to Bermondsey and into the the safety of Anspach & Hobday's brewery and taproom.

There are 12 beers on tap and many more bottles: a collection that includes all manner of porters, stouts and IPAs that'll reeducate your tastebuds in the wonders of good beer - hoppy, malty, dark, light, whatever your preference, they should have something for you. As if that wasn't enough, they let you bring your own food, and yes, Maltby Street Market is just down the road. Now you just need to find somewhere to dry off from your swim.

With pint prices at an all-time high, it's time to up your beer game. None of the bog-standard big dogs - if you're gonna be shelling out the big bucks you might as well be shelling it out for a more refined variety of the brown stuff.

The Bottle Shop focuses on brewing world class beer that's rich, sour, refreshing, tangy and everything in between. With a selection of over 50 bottles, and all the industrial-chic vibes you could reasonably expect, this is a great spot to begin your Rocky-style training montage of getting good at beer.
